[1] South Korea, 3 new cases, 1 new death - MOH 21 Jun 2015
Date: 21 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH [in Korean, trans. by Korean subscribers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323630


MERS-CoV Daily Update
-Total number of cases now stands at 169: 101 currently receiving treatment (59.8 percent), 43 discharged (25.4 percent), 25 dead (14.8 percent).
-3 additional case and 7 additional recoveries compared to previous day's numbers; 1 new fatality.
-Of the 101 receiving treatment: 87 in stable condition (86.1 percent), 16 reportedly unstable (13.9 percent).
-78 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 59 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 32 are of hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced 3 new cases of MERS-CoV - bringing the total tally up to 169 - as of 6 AM KST, 21 Jun 2015.
- The number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 5 since yesterday [20 Jun 2015] and currently stands at 101 (59.8 percent of total); 7 have recovered, bringing the number up to 43 (25.4 percent); the fatality count currently stands at 25 (14.8 percent).

New Cases
- 3 additional cases has been confirmed since yesterday
- Patient no. 167 (53 year old male) was hospitalized in the same Kyung Hee University Medical Center ED as Patient no. 76 on 5 Jun 2015.
- Patient no. 168 (36 year old male) is a radiology technician that reportedly took x-ray images of Patient no. 76 on 6 Jun 2015 at Konkuk University Medical Center
- Patient no. 169 served as Patient no. 135's attending physician at Seoul Samsung Medical Center ICU.
*Patients no. 167 and 168 were identified while under hospital quarantine after Patient no. 76 was diagnosed with the virus.

New Dischargees
- Patients 11 (79 year old female), 29 (77 year old female), 43 (24 year old female), 107 (64 year old female), 134 (68 year old female), 139 (64 year old female), and 142 (31 year old male) have been discharged in between 19 Jun 2015 and the morning of 20 Jun 2015, bringing the total number of recoveries to 43.
- Dischargees underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 43 total recoveries, 24 (55.8 percent) are male with 19 (44.2 percent) being female; 14 have been in the 40s (32.6 percent), 8 each have been in their 50s and 60s (18.6 percent each), 5 patients each have been in the 70s (11.6 percent each), with 4 patients each having been in their 20s and 30s (9.3 percent each).

New Fatalities
- Patient no. 112 (63 year old male, myocardial ischemia/diabetes) was pronounced dead around 1800 of 20 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 25.
- Of the 25 reported fatalities to date, 18 have been male (72 percent), while 7 have been female (28 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s with 9 (36 percent) fatalities, followed by 8 (32 percent) fatalities in the 70s, 4 (16 percent) in the 50s, 3 (12 percent) in the 80s and 1 (4 percent) in the 40s.
- 23 of the 25 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD, cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 169 total cases reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 46.2 percent (78 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 34.9 percent of total cases (59), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is report to be at 18.9 percent (32)

- Male infectees comprise 61.5 percent of the total cases (104), and females, 38.5 percent (65)
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 35 patients (20.7 percent) are in the 50s, 34 (20.1 percent) are in their 60s, 30 are in their 40s (17.8 percent), 27 are in their 70s (16 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (15.4 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 21 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 4035 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 22.4 percent lower than previous day's numbers (a decrease of 1162); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 8812, which equates to an increase of 1361 compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 4035 under quarantine, 3296 are under home isolation (a 25.8 percent decrease, or a decrease of 1149), while the number of hospital quarantines has also decreased by 13 (1.7 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 739.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The official tallies for 20 Jun 2015 were not posted until after yesterday's update was published. The media report that was used mentioned there were no new cases and no new fatalities, but it did not mention there were 6 new discharges from the hospital, explaining why the number of discharges is now up to 43.

As of the morning of 21 Jun 2015 (Korean time) there have now been 169 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection including 25 deaths in South Korea (reported case fatality rate of 14.8 percent). The 3 newly confirmed cases mentioned in today's update are all 4th generation cases as the case contacts they had were 3rd generation cases (patient no.76 and no.135 were both 3rd generation cases. Two of the 3 newly confirmed cases are in healthcare workers - 1 physician and 1 radiology technician. To date there has been only 1 probable 5th generation case (case no. 163, a nurse whose contacts are still under investigation but include a 4th generation case).

All cases to date can be traced to contact within the healthcare environment with the exception of an ambulance driver and presumed EMT working with the ambulance transporting case no.76 to the hospitals.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of South Korea can be found at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3453094,195. - Mod.MPP]

