[2] South Korea - MOH update 20 Jun 2015
Date: 20 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH, English page [edited]
http://english.mw.go.kr/front_eng/sg/ssg0111vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=1001&MENU_ID=100111&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323609


Statistics (No. of persons)
Confirmed Case: 166
Discharged: 30
Death: 24
Under Treatment: 112

Case No.166 is a family member of the patient who stayed at the Samsung Medical Center (Seoul) between 25 May 2015 and 5 Jun 2015.

Profile of fatalities:
Male: 17 (71 percent), female: 7 (29 percent), persons above 60: 19 (79 percent)

- 22 (92 percent) were high-risk, old-age patients with underlying medical conditions such as cardio-cerebrovascular disease, cancer and chronic respiratory disease.

Of the 112 patients currently under treatment: 16 are in severe conditions, and 96 in moderate conditions

Confirmed Case: 116
Being Tested: 132
Under Quarantine: 5930
- home quarantine: 5161
- in hospital quarantine: 769
- released from quarantine: 5535

Update on the Samsung Medical Center (Seoul)
- Infection prevention and control measures have been scaled up. 41 930 people who visited the hospital during the periods of high MERS exposure have been reached through text messages or phone calls. The number of contacts increased to 7000 as a result of using a more conservative counting method.

- Residents of Seoul should report to the Dasan Call Center (120) or the official website of the Seoul metropolitan city. Residents of other areas should report through the Korean government's official website for the MERS outbreak (http://mers.go.kr).

- The government understands the ordeal of those under house quarantine and expresses its deepest appreciation for their cooperation. Complying with quarantine measures is essential for stopping the further spread of MERS-CoV. The Director-General of WHO, Dr. Margaret Chan, also stressed that the cooperation of the community and the general public is crucial for ending the MERS outbreak as early as possible. Thus, continued cooperation will be greatly appreciated.

- The government will ensure that 2650 affiliated hospitals will provide medical services and prescriptions to the patients who were cared for by the Samsung Medical Center prior to the MERS outbreak.

Funerals
- Individuals under house quarantine will be allowed to visit their loved ones in critical conditions and attend their death beds while wearing protective gear. It is also possible for the quarantined individuals to carry the corpses of their loved ones to cremation facilities. However, there will be a limit to the number of those who can be part of this funeral process.

The quarantined individuals must adhere to the following instructions:
- Discuss with hospital staff how many family members will attend the funeral
- Contact local public health centers to borrow protective gear and wear them
- Go to the hospital in a vehicle provided by the public health center
- Keep your protective gear on until you return home

Update on Hospitals Under Strict Control
- Proactive measures have been taken to stop further infections at Gang-dong Kyung Hee University Hospital where a number of dialysis patients were exposed to MERS (109).

The list of 109 patients was sent to all dialysis facilities across the nation through HIRA (Health Insurance Review and Assessment Service). Those on the list are banned from visiting other dialysis rooms at will.

- As of today [20 Jun 2015], new non-MERS patients cannot be admitted to the hospital. A dialysis patient with high MERS exposure will be given priority in entering an isolated single room if a patient is discharged. Individuals under house quarantine will be strictly monitored and be transported by the designated ambulances if necessary.

- It was found that case no.165 was not infected within a dialysis room. Nonetheless, the government will strengthen cooperation with the hospital in order to prevent the virus from spreading through dialysis rooms.

- Previously, 65 patients were put under cohort quarantine on the 7th floor along with confirmed cases at Asan Chungmu Hospital. Currently, among these quarantined individuals, 48 have been isolated in single rooms and 17 have been relocated to another hospital in order to strengthen infection control.

- Additional medical staff members have been recruited through the Ministry of National Defense, the Korean Hospital Association (KHA) and the Korean Nurses Association (KNA) to support the Hospitals Under Strict Control whose staff members are suffering from increasing fatigue.

- The government expresses its appreciation to the private sector, KHA and KNA for their active cooperation, and asks the Korean Medical Association (KMA) for their participation.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above information comes from the English pages of the Korean MOH website. The information provided on the hospitals is new, with mention of the possible exposures in the dialysis unit of one of the hospitals and the actions that are being taken. It is also impressive to see the number of individuals that the MOH is attempting to contact re: possible exposure in the Samsung hospital ... 41 930 individuals who were in the hospital during periods of "high MERS exposure", with contact being made through text messages or phone calls ... a massive undertaking. - Mod.MPP]

